column4: "tweet": "11) It‚Äôs certainly not hard to envision a scenario where an extended shutdown
column5: coupled with a slow resumption of business forces $TSLA to seek additional liquidity over the summer or risk a restructuring.  Much depends on $TSLA‚Äôs ability to quickly cut costs."

column4: "tweet": "8) An add‚Äôl consideration is how much cash does $TSLA need to survive a bankruptcy. They can‚Äôt simply take cash to zero. When GM filed in 2009
column5: they had $11bn of cash on their balance sheet. It‚Äôs hard to envision a successful restructuring if $TSLA files with less than $2bn cash.  https://t.co/iB9HowgUOW"

column4: "tweet": "7) Ultimately
column5: I don‚Äôt believe the banks will balk at funding if it means $TSLA files.  Therefore I view the $500mm as legitimate liquidity ‚Äì although it‚Äôs worth noting that there are outlier scenarios in which this money is not truly available."

column4: "tweet": "6) The last $500mm is undrawn availability under $TSLA‚Äôs Credit Agreement.  This availability is subject to a number of borrowing tests
column5: borrowing base requirements and a material adverse change clause.  A detailed covenant review is beyond the scope of this thread.  https://t.co/9YCWNRqj03"

column4: "tweet": "5) $1bn of availability is for vehicle and solar leases.  These lines can only be drawn to fund vehicle leases and cannot be used for general corporate purposes (in lieu of receiving cash from a customer
